# Breakdown on New York State crime rates

        New York State, like other states in America, deal with high amounts of crime. Crime can vary from property damage, larceny and motor to violent crimes such as assault, murder and rape. Here, we will explore the variations of how that crime has changed from the years 1960 to 2019 and analyze potential reasons for how the crime rates have changed year to year.

## New York State Crimes
            
        The following image shows how the rates of property related crimes has changed from 1960 to 2019 in New York State.

![Scatter Plot of Rates of All Property related crimes per year](image-2.png)

        As seen by the diagram the rates of property related crimes has sort of a roller coaster pattern going up and down at different spots before eventually having a massive decline just after 1990. As the internet and technology as a whole increased, fighting crime became much easier for law enforcement. The introduction of CompStat, a data driven command system, forced commanders to track and address crime trends directly. This was a model for accountability that other agencies would eventually adopt.

![Scatter Plot of Totals for All Violent Related Crimes](image-3.png)

        This image is similar to the above image because it also has a sort of roller coaster style look going up and down and then eventually dying down to much smaller numbers in the years above 2000. I believe, similar to the property visualization, that technology played a big part in stopping criminals, and murderers. Better searching and profiling technologies allows authorities to capture and track down murderers than in the 80s and 90s when violent crimes were at a peak. ALso, security cameras and better quality on monitors allows identifying what happened and who was involved much easier. Overall, this graphic is fairly similar to others in that technology played a big role in limiting any kind of crime.


![Scatter Plot of Pennsylvania's Rates of All Property Related Crimes](image-5.png)

        We are going to change up the graphics a little to show other states that are both similar to New York geographically in size and population. Here is Pennsylvania and their property related crimes from 1960 to 2019. In a way, the graphic is similar to New York but also different. The shape is more like a mountain where it peaks at the top and has a sort of zig-zag shape before also plummetting down at around 2005.

        Larceny has been one of Pennsylvania's biggest issues historically with period spikes and dips. Due to economic growth, urban renewal and policing strategies, Pennsylvania experienced a sharp drop in property crimes during the early 2000s. Similar to New York State, technology played a crucial role in lowering all sorts of crime.

![Scatter Plot of Florida's Total Violent Crimes](image-6.png)

        Similar to the above graphic, we will be comparing Florida to New York in terms of their management of total violent crimes in the past 70 or so years. Florida has been infamously known for their poor management of crimes in general but why? Well, this theory may be proven wrong as the graphs between New York and Florida are similar in a way. Looking at the data on the left, both peaked at around the same time and both settled down at around the same amount of total violent crimes per year that were reported. However, New York began their drop off sooner than Florida did, as New York started at around 1990 while Florida wasn't until around 2010. 
        This comes with a big limitation with New York City playing a huge deciding factor role on how the data is dispersed. Majority of New York's population and crime comes from the city and therefore doesn't fully count for the rest of the state.

